1
00:00:01,330 --> 00:00:03,914
Foundation course two, talk three.

2
00:00:05,275 --> 00:00:06,097
The end of guilt.

3
00:00:07,958 --> 00:00:12,605
Guilt can be a real problem for us and it can become a major cause of our disease.

4
00:00:14,208 --> 00:00:24,503
Whenever we satisfy our desires, be they desires to have something or desires to do away with something, if these desires are satisfied at the expense of another, guilt arises.

5
00:00:25,495 --> 00:00:30,943
the knowledge of having done harm arises, and with it, in differing degrees, shame and dread.

6
00:00:32,304 --> 00:00:50,710
Although these days we've come to see this in a very negative light, actually this is a healthy reaction, for the fact that guilt, shame and dread have arisen means that the doer is still in contact with the heart, that inner compassionate part of us that knows such things cause suffering and cannot bear it.

7
00:00:52,106 --> 00:00:56,493
If these reactions do not arise, what is there stopping us behaving in harmful ways?

8
00:00:57,655 --> 00:01:09,352
If society did not have moral code or moral law, a basic agreement among its citizens on how to live together without doing each other harm, it would certainly be a case of dog-eat-dog.

9
00:01:09,993 --> 00:01:18,587
The whole system of law is about being able to judge impartially any case of harm that arises so that the aggrieved can be compensated and the doer checked.

10
00:01:18,921 --> 00:01:25,248
The idea of a society protecting its citizens from the harm of others is accepted unequivocally.

11
00:01:26,271 --> 00:01:30,936
This is a pure reason, shall we say, for a police force to stop society eating itself.

12
00:01:33,519 --> 00:01:36,882
The inability to accept guilt causes individuals a lot of problems.

13
00:01:37,743 --> 00:01:41,507
The idea that we shouldn't feel guilty causes us a lot of problems.

14
00:01:42,248 --> 00:01:45,552
They both repress what is a perfectly natural response of the heart.

15
00:01:46,275 --> 00:01:52,503
Just as a good heart responds to acts of cruelty with horror, so it responds to a person's own acts of cruelty with horror.

16
00:01:53,965 --> 00:02:00,391
When we read in the newspapers that a woman or a boy had been murdered or sexually abused, feelings of shock and intense dislike arise.

17
00:02:01,153 --> 00:02:08,622
When we ourselves do something against our own model code, the same sort of horror emotions arise directed towards ourselves.

18
00:02:09,461 --> 00:02:18,191
This sort of guilt reaction and the ensuing shame and dread of consequences are our internal guardians, stopping us doing what we know to be harmful.

19
00:02:19,092 --> 00:02:20,032
But things do go wrong.

20
00:02:22,195 --> 00:02:26,159
Ever since we were children, we have been told in varying degrees how bad we are.

21
00:02:26,781 --> 00:02:32,567
We are variously cheeky, naughty, selfish, cruel, called nuisances, good-for-nothings, liars, thieves, and so on.

22
00:02:33,543 --> 00:02:36,105
This sort of labelling really gets into the child.

23
00:02:36,907 --> 00:02:45,237
The famous French writer and playwright Jean Genet writes how when he was a boy, he was told he was a thief, so he said to himself, yes, that's what I am.

24
00:02:46,019 --> 00:02:46,919
He ended up in jail.

25
00:02:48,062 --> 00:02:54,909
I remember myself going into a newsagent as a young boy, ten years old or so, and asking for my father's newspaper.

26
00:02:55,972 --> 00:03:03,381
I must have pushed in the queue or asked with some imperious tone in my voice, because the assistant said, you're presumptuous.

27
00:03:04,558 --> 00:03:07,683
I felt really embarrassed about it, I felt so humiliated.

28
00:03:08,224 --> 00:03:12,230
Worse, because I couldn't give a cheeky answer, since I didn't know what it meant.

29
00:03:13,372 --> 00:03:15,014
Though I did realise it was belittling.

30
00:03:16,317 --> 00:03:26,532
I harboured a great grudge against that assistant, and often fantasised situations where I turned the tables and gleefully exclaimed, ''Aha, you see, you're the one who's presumptuous!''

31
00:03:28,183 --> 00:03:35,652
Both these two factors of accusations and labeling, judgments by others of our personalities, become internalized.

32
00:03:36,133 --> 00:03:37,414
We believe them.

33
00:03:37,435 --> 00:03:53,414
So that later on in life, these self-accusations, derogatory self-definitions, denigrating self-judgments, all go to create a very uncomfortable feeling within ourselves, feelings of inadequacy, of being naturally no good, evil, rotten to the core.

34
00:03:54,187 --> 00:04:01,097
It doesn't help much either if you've been brought up in a religion where a wrathful God, devilish demons and hellfire have dominated.

35
00:04:01,657 --> 00:04:08,866
Luckily, I was brought up in a Christian religion that stressed the love, compassion and forgiving nature of Jesus and his Father.

36
00:04:09,288 --> 00:04:11,531
So personally, I didn't have any problems that way.

37
00:04:13,954 --> 00:04:17,278
This is not to say that guilt is not known in Buddhist countries.

38
00:04:17,298 --> 00:04:18,019
Far from it.

39
00:04:18,420 --> 00:04:22,988
Often the doctrine of karma is taught only in its negative aspects.

40
00:04:23,288 --> 00:04:25,593
The evil consequences are inescapable.

41
00:04:26,615 --> 00:04:29,399
This also can lead to an inordinate fear of consequences.

42
00:04:30,781 --> 00:04:43,062
Although the scriptures are full of tales of the most horrific consequences, the Buddha says in the Dhammapada, if a person does what is good, he should do it again and again.

43
00:04:43,615 --> 00:04:46,680
If a person does what is good, she should delight in it.

44
00:04:47,182 --> 00:04:49,646
The accumulation of merit leads to happiness.

45
00:04:52,411 --> 00:04:57,983
We need to bring such thoughts to mind whenever we are thinking of unwholesome results of our actions.

46
00:04:58,543 --> 00:05:01,589
We can affect the future by the good we do now.

47
00:05:03,240 --> 00:05:05,425
So we can say that there are two types of guilt.

48
00:05:06,026 --> 00:05:08,449
The one, a natural response to wrongdoing.

49
00:05:08,810 --> 00:05:15,302
The other, an unrealistic response caused by underlying accusatory self-definitions and unresolved guilt.

50
00:05:16,725 --> 00:05:17,747
How do we overcome this?

51
00:05:18,848 --> 00:05:21,012
What can we do about such states of mind?

52
00:05:22,072 --> 00:05:29,783
The importance of this lies in the fact that restlessness and anxiety caused by guilt are both great hindrances in the meditation practice.

53
00:05:30,684 --> 00:05:34,629
When we are restless and anxious, the mind is said to be like a turbulent pool.

54
00:05:35,509 --> 00:05:38,512
We are unable to see beyond the surface of waves and splashes.

55
00:05:39,875 --> 00:05:45,622
If our insight is to grow, we need very much to bring peace to this pool, to clear the mind of all guilt.

56
00:05:46,682 --> 00:05:52,029
Remember, the moral laws of Buddhism are also rules of mental health.

57
00:05:53,392 --> 00:05:58,918
Let us return to little Lily, whom we left glum, unable to have ice cream she wanted.

58
00:06:00,399 --> 00:06:03,403
Lily wanted to have ice cream, but it was too near lunchtime.

59
00:06:03,764 --> 00:06:05,406
She got angry and very depressed about it.

60
00:06:06,307 --> 00:06:10,550
Even though her parents did get her some ice cream in the afternoon, she still felt aggrieved.

61
00:06:11,112 --> 00:06:13,394
Children have their own thoughts, they're little persons.

62
00:06:14,675 --> 00:06:19,079
No matter what parents do, they can never be totally responsible for the child's behaviour.

63
00:06:19,651 --> 00:06:25,077
Such total responsibility presumes total control of the child's development and environment.

64
00:06:26,079 --> 00:06:34,250
But not only are there other factors at play, such as friends, other adults, the media, and so on, there is the indomitable little mind of the child herself.

65
00:06:35,872 --> 00:06:37,495
Lily is not a scheming child.

66
00:06:38,456 --> 00:06:41,641
She's just decided that if she wants ice cream, she should have some.

67
00:06:42,040 --> 00:06:42,401
Why not?

68
00:06:43,483 --> 00:06:48,509
That afternoon, Mum also bought a whole box of vanilla ice cream and put it in the freezer.

69
00:06:48,928 --> 00:06:54,233
Next day, during a quiet afternoon, the image of that box rose in the mind of little Lily.

70
00:06:55,095 --> 00:07:07,166
She quietly slipped out of the sitting room, looking very busy, went to the freezer, doled herself out a goodly portion, and crept upstairs to her bedroom, where she feasted in paradise with her dolls.

71
00:07:08,247 --> 00:07:12,072
It never occurred to her that the hole in the ice cream would be noticed.

72
00:07:13,632 --> 00:07:18,598
Well, of course, that evening, when Mum went to get the dessert, half was gone, and the alarm went out.

73
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:21,163
Lily was commanded to report immediately.

74
00:07:22,225 --> 00:07:25,269
Lily arrives looking innocent enough, though inwardly trembling.

75
00:07:25,911 --> 00:07:29,456
When that sort of alarm goes up, it means she's done something really wrong.

76
00:07:30,939 --> 00:07:32,401
She knows it's got to be the ice cream.

77
00:07:33,382 --> 00:07:37,108
It is at this point that Lily is beginning to suffer the karmic results of her actions.

78
00:07:37,850 --> 00:07:42,598
Up till now, she's been enjoying the karmic results of satisfying her desire for ice cream.

79
00:07:43,278 --> 00:07:45,041
But she got it by unlawful means.

80
00:07:45,511 --> 00:07:53,480
The product of those unlawful means is now her trembling as she meets the female deity in her wrathful aspect, the angry mum.

81
00:07:55,422 --> 00:08:01,009
What happens from now on is going to be crucial to Lily's future behaviour and her attitude concerning the model law.

82
00:08:02,009 --> 00:08:05,454
Will mum reinforce her feelings of fear by giving her a slapping?

83
00:08:06,595 --> 00:08:11,721
Will she turn the accent onto naughtiness and evil, calling Lily a do-no-good-little-thief?

84
00:08:13,372 --> 00:08:15,154
Will she give Lily room to explain herself?

85
00:08:15,896 --> 00:08:18,839
Will she appeal to Lily's better nature, to her sense of remorse?

86
00:08:19,740 --> 00:08:22,925
Will she demand Lily pay a price, that she be punished in some way?

87
00:08:23,846 --> 00:08:27,271
Will she forgive Lily totally, and ask her never to do such a thing again?

88
00:08:28,514 --> 00:08:30,456
Will she ask Lily to make such a resolution?

89
00:08:31,437 --> 00:08:37,667
Will she forgive Lily, but with dire warnings of what will happen the next time such things happen?

90
00:08:37,687 --> 00:08:38,788
Mum's options are varied.

91
00:08:39,889 --> 00:08:41,893
She could have even decided to ignore it.

92
00:08:42,565 --> 00:08:50,613
She could even have slapped Lily hard for what she did, but told her, if she wants to steal, she should do it from the shops and not from home.

93
00:08:51,273 --> 00:08:52,313
There's honour amongst thieves.

94
00:08:53,755 --> 00:09:00,302
However Mum has reacted, my bet is that she has done so exactly as her mother and father did to her.

95
00:09:01,182 --> 00:09:05,346
She has internalised, made her own, her parents' way of handling immoral conduct.

96
00:09:05,667 --> 00:09:08,309
In fact, she treats herself like that.

97
00:09:10,812 --> 00:09:12,453
Before we can investigate further...

98
00:09:12,772 --> 00:09:16,135
We need to be clear what the place of punishment is in the law of karma.

99
00:09:17,177 --> 00:09:21,922
The Buddha stated that the consequences of our actions, good and bad, were inescapable.

100
00:09:22,562 --> 00:09:25,706
But they are consequences, not rewards or punishments.

101
00:09:26,407 --> 00:09:29,770
No divine law, no god, punishes or rewards us.

102
00:09:30,172 --> 00:09:31,773
It is simply a matter of results.

103
00:09:32,855 --> 00:09:36,238
If I turn up late for work, fail to do a good job, I get sacked.

104
00:09:37,019 --> 00:09:39,182
I can't say the boss or the system punished me.

105
00:09:39,861 --> 00:09:42,205
The sacking is a result of my working practices.

106
00:09:42,961 --> 00:09:48,167
If I mindlessly handle a boiling kettle and scorch myself, I can't say the kettle has punished me.

107
00:09:48,908 --> 00:09:53,153
Punishment is something invented by human beings to inflict upon each other.

108
00:09:54,333 --> 00:10:09,272
Punishment is either getting even, an eye for an eye, or it's to slake our thirst for revenge, or it is out of a mistaken understanding that punishment is a deterrent which will stop the wrongdoer without unwholesome side effects.

109
00:10:10,804 --> 00:10:19,215
Whatever reasons are given for punishment, as far as the Buddha's understanding goes, it's something human beings lay on the wrongdoer as an extra.

110
00:10:20,255 --> 00:10:29,265
For whether the punisher or the wrongdoer likes it or not, the unwholesome consequences of the wrong action will manifest themselves in the goodness of time.

111
00:10:30,668 --> 00:10:32,529
The Buddha appeals to our better nature.

112
00:10:33,711 --> 00:10:35,673
All are afraid of the stick.

113
00:10:35,693 --> 00:10:36,794
All fear death.

114
00:10:37,298 --> 00:10:41,481
putting oneself in another's place, one should not beat or kill another.

115
00:10:44,485 --> 00:10:55,196
The concept of punishment is alien to Buddhism, and unlike other religious systems or secular codes of law, you will not find in the scriptures any lists of appropriate punishment for crime.

116
00:10:56,356 --> 00:11:04,825
For it is understood that when we do harm to another, even if it is legal or socially acceptable, it can only be done with aversion in the mind.

117
00:11:05,951 --> 00:11:08,355
There is no such thing as righteous retribution.

118
00:11:09,375 --> 00:11:14,201
Whatever person A does that is unskillful, he will reap the painful consequences.

119
00:11:15,142 --> 00:11:18,025
The consequences themselves will be the just desert.

120
00:11:19,047 --> 00:11:27,296
Person B, who wants to exact punishment, a further suffering, who calls for the cat, the gallows, solitary confinement, does it for unwholesome reasons.

121
00:11:28,336 --> 00:11:32,701
The righteous punisher will also receive their just deserts for their cruelty.

122
00:11:33,626 --> 00:11:38,553
But there is a deeper reason, still, why punishment is inimicable to the Buddha's path.

123
00:11:38,875 --> 00:11:43,861
And that is because what is at root fault is not an evil nature, but sheer ignorance.

124
00:11:44,643 --> 00:11:56,279
A wrongdoer, perhaps better termed a mistaken doer, must be approached with compassion, with firmness, no doubt, but with the intention of showing that person the unwholesome consequences of their action.

125
00:11:58,243 --> 00:12:02,149
Now, mum has done a lot of meditation and given a lot of thought to this whole problem.

126
00:12:02,736 --> 00:12:09,803
Although she is a fire with divine wrathfulness, within this great display lies a heart of compassion, the heart of wisdom.

127
00:12:10,884 --> 00:12:15,509
First, there is the great owning up, I did it, the acceptance.

128
00:12:16,591 --> 00:12:19,994
Then, Lily has to be shown the consequences of her deed.

129
00:12:20,715 --> 00:12:23,538
Not enough ice cream to go around, hardly a spoonful each.

130
00:12:24,197 --> 00:12:27,761
How does Lily feel about that, depriving everyone else of their ice cream?

131
00:12:28,663 --> 00:12:32,726
Slowly, Lily is coaxed to a position of seeing the harm she's done

132
00:12:33,297 --> 00:12:35,719
She's allowed to offer mitigating circumstances.

133
00:12:36,399 --> 00:12:39,003
She didn't know she was taking everybody else's ice cream.

134
00:12:39,984 --> 00:12:43,827
Remorse abounds, perhaps a few tears, but Mum can't stop there.

135
00:12:44,567 --> 00:12:49,994
These tears could be tainted with relief, for Lily knows from her Mum's tone she won't be slapped.

136
00:12:50,553 --> 00:12:52,035
Or tainted with sympathy-seeking.

137
00:12:52,395 --> 00:12:54,677
Who cannot be softened by the tears of a child?

138
00:12:55,538 --> 00:12:56,240
Children are clever.

139
00:12:57,120 --> 00:12:59,202
No, the consequences must be faced.

140
00:12:59,538 --> 00:13:04,384
She is asked to agree not to have ice cream so that others can have a proper share.

141
00:13:04,884 --> 00:13:05,525
Lily agrees.

142
00:13:06,647 --> 00:13:11,894
But still there's an important ingredient missing, which will allow Lily to move towards wholesomeness.

143
00:13:12,975 --> 00:13:19,803
All right, she's made good the obvious consequences of her deed, but how does her heart know that she has done enough?

144
00:13:20,784 --> 00:13:24,870
She knows everything is back to normal when her mother forgives her.

145
00:13:25,794 --> 00:13:33,221
Lily's heart is greatly relieved, for now she sees the wrathful deity in her benign aspect of forgiveness and radiant love.

146
00:13:34,062 --> 00:13:38,788
A hug and a cuddle heals the internal wound, but still the process is not complete.

147
00:13:39,668 --> 00:13:40,769
Lily has confessed.

148
00:13:41,210 --> 00:13:42,171
She's been remorseful.

149
00:13:42,572 --> 00:13:44,133
She's accepted the consequences.

150
00:13:44,494 --> 00:13:46,034
She will make good reparation.

151
00:13:46,716 --> 00:13:50,058
She has received forgiveness, but what will stop her doing it again?

152
00:13:50,099 --> 00:13:52,741
Right understanding is not enough.

153
00:13:53,462 --> 00:13:55,784
Right intention must also be made.

154
00:13:56,474 --> 00:14:04,003
In the midst of that forgiving embrace, Lily finds it easy to make a firm and unshakable resolution never to do such a thing again.

155
00:14:04,984 --> 00:14:09,970
How important it is for the goddess to say she believes Lily will never do it again.

156
00:14:11,532 --> 00:14:24,388
Later on at the dinner table, when the sad tale is retold to explain why Lily is not having ice cream, everyone is moved to share their ice cream, and Lily learns that her good deed of making good has other wonderful consequences.

157
00:14:25,414 --> 00:14:28,998
Now, I apologize if I've been pulling the heartstrings a bit here.

158
00:14:30,259 --> 00:14:31,500
I know it's never quite so easy.

159
00:14:32,380 --> 00:14:34,302
I know wonderful endings are miracles.

160
00:14:35,442 --> 00:14:39,046
But at least here we have a model we can work on to develop our own strategies.

161
00:14:40,086 --> 00:14:41,288
All the steps are important.

162
00:14:41,989 --> 00:14:48,894
And it is all important we not only treat children like this, but adults and ourselves.

163
00:14:51,397 --> 00:14:55,320
To overcome the horror of guilt, the shame and the dread in whatever degree,

164
00:14:55,705 --> 00:15:02,250
there has first of all got to be an open acceptance of the fact and the realization of the ensuing consequences.

165
00:15:03,251 --> 00:15:06,575
Then remorse arises and sorrow and with it the apology.

166
00:15:07,635 --> 00:15:24,631
Next we need to do something about the consequences and if nothing can be done, then we must learn to console ourselves with the fact that it is not within our powers to do anything and that we must readily accept the results of what we have done with patience, a willingness to suffer them gladly.

167
00:15:25,759 --> 00:15:26,841
Then comes forgiveness.

168
00:15:28,304 --> 00:15:31,772
It's a great help in healing our hearts if the victim forgives us.

169
00:15:32,474 --> 00:15:35,900
But if that is not forthcoming, we have to be able to forgive ourselves.

170
00:15:37,244 --> 00:15:44,258
If we are dogged by thoughts of, I can't forgive myself, not for that, then we must turn the stream of compassion inwards.

171
00:15:45,232 --> 00:15:48,155
we need to ask ourselves why we can't forgive ourselves.

172
00:15:48,817 --> 00:15:59,669
After all, what does forgiveness mean but, alright, I've done wrong, I've done what I can to put things right, I've learnt my lesson, so I'm going to be kind and pardon myself.

173
00:16:01,171 --> 00:16:07,038
If when we talk to ourselves like this, feelings of self-hate arise, these must be observed and not entertained.

174
00:16:08,460 --> 00:16:12,303
We also need to be aware of our inverted pride which is subtly saying,

175
00:16:12,924 --> 00:16:15,587
I won't forgive myself till they forgive me.

176
00:16:17,389 --> 00:16:26,018
This inability to pardon ourselves, to be unforgiving towards our own faults, needs to be constantly tackled with the practice of loving kindness directed inwards.

177
00:16:27,499 --> 00:16:33,885
Slowly, these self-accusatory, unforgiving voices will trouble us less and less until they disappear altogether.

178
00:16:34,907 --> 00:16:39,230
If we fail to do this, we have simply internalized the wrathful deity.

179
00:16:39,831 --> 00:16:42,274
We become our own punishers and executioners.

180
00:16:42,928 --> 00:16:45,511
The consequences of our wrongdoings are painful enough.

181
00:16:46,052 --> 00:16:48,575
There's no need to load it with self-inflicted wounds.

182
00:16:50,297 --> 00:16:51,759
Finally, what seals the wound?

183
00:16:52,119 --> 00:16:57,924
The firm resolution to abstain from such actions in the future, to determine to be forever on our guard.

184
00:16:59,267 --> 00:17:02,890
This resolution gives us confidence, and success builds on success.

185
00:17:03,652 --> 00:17:06,674
Yes, I used to do things like that, but I don't now.

186
00:17:08,073 --> 00:17:10,477
This returns our self-respect and self-esteem.

187
00:17:10,916 --> 00:17:18,769
At last, our hearts, split into all sorts of conflicting emotions, return to their pure base of balance and tranquility.

188
00:17:21,633 --> 00:17:28,983
The ability to move through these stages becomes increasingly more important the more we travel along the spiritual path.

189
00:17:30,652 --> 00:17:41,022
The Buddha was forever talking of the importance of moral behavior that a whole third part of the Tipitika is devoted to the higher morality of the monastic life.

190
00:17:42,365 --> 00:17:47,269
The Tipitika is what the Buddhist scriptures are called and means literally the three baskets.

191
00:17:48,491 --> 00:17:58,903
The first being the discourses , the second being the monastic discipline , and the third the Abhidhamma .

192
00:18:00,857 --> 00:18:05,045
The higher morality of the monastic life is meant to speed the ardent towards liberation.

193
00:18:05,905 --> 00:18:15,962
There are 227 rules at base, but these are compounded with refinements and later commentarial additions, on top of which each culture and each monastery adds its own rules.

194
00:18:16,983 --> 00:18:20,049
The whole idea is to keep the monastic on the straight and narrow.

195
00:18:21,171 --> 00:18:26,460
This is very important for lay Buddhists to know, because often they support monks unwisely,

196
00:18:26,795 --> 00:18:28,759
tempting them with things they ought not to have.

197
00:18:29,118 --> 00:18:32,486
For instance, a monk is not supposed to wear any sort of jewelry.

198
00:18:33,386 --> 00:18:36,834
Now, it's a moot point as to whether a watch can be considered so.

199
00:18:37,494 --> 00:18:40,721
A lot of monks overcome the problem by having pocket calculator watches.

200
00:18:41,903 --> 00:18:46,592
But there is a great difference between buying a monk a simple timepiece and giving him a gold watch.

201
00:18:47,837 --> 00:18:58,615
Now, it may not come as a great surprise to you, but the community hold what is called a patimokha ceremony every 8th and 13th, 14th day of the lunar month.

202
00:18:58,635 --> 00:19:03,784
The whole set of rules are recited, and monks confess to each other any transgressions they have committed.

203
00:19:05,467 --> 00:19:08,090
Some are serious enough to cause expulsion from the order.

204
00:19:08,914 --> 00:19:20,275
The consequences of breaking a more serious rule is to suffer isolation from the community for six nights, during which time the monk is meant to reflect on his actions and the community to reflect on how to respond.

205
00:19:21,317 --> 00:19:26,425
Confiscation is also carried out if a monk owns up to having something he ought not to have.

206
00:19:27,207 --> 00:19:31,294
But the vast majority of transgressions are forgiven on the telling.

207
00:19:32,336 --> 00:19:38,805
Do you think such a thing is possible in families, where members own up to bad temper and so on, and are forgiven and exhorted to change?

208
00:19:40,686 --> 00:19:44,971
There is also a formula monks use when they hurt another monk in any way.

209
00:19:45,673 --> 00:19:47,013
Its formula may interest you.

210
00:19:48,516 --> 00:19:57,507
Forgive me, venerable sir, for my wrongdoing, done carelessly to the venerable one, by way of the three doors, of mind, speech, and body.

211
00:19:58,867 --> 00:19:59,388
I forgive you.

212
00:19:59,829 --> 00:20:01,010
You should forgive me.

213
00:20:01,767 --> 00:20:03,028
I forgive you, venerable sir.

214
00:20:04,791 --> 00:20:09,118
The interesting thing in this formula is the magnanimity asked of the victim.

215
00:20:09,479 --> 00:20:10,421
He also forgives.

216
00:20:11,462 --> 00:20:14,508
It takes two to quarrel, and it takes two to forgive.

217
00:20:15,730 --> 00:20:22,861
Perhaps mum and dad were wrong to buy the ice cream and store it so obviously, knowing little Lily's predilection, her little problem.

218
00:20:24,262 --> 00:20:28,450
Perhaps they should have warned her not to take any, or told her when she would get some.

219
00:20:29,272 --> 00:20:33,818
We often unwittingly lay traps for others and then expect them to take all the blame.

220
00:20:34,819 --> 00:20:41,087
How much of our present-day violence, for instance, can we apportion to social policies and how much to personal responsibility?

221
00:20:43,832 --> 00:20:57,288
The reason why we must be able to handle our unskillful behaviour is because we shall keep on tripping over the moral law, keep on creating unwholesome karma, no matter how insignificant, till the very day of our total liberation.

222
00:20:58,163 --> 00:21:07,601
Not until we become Arahats, when the root causes of our unwholesome actions, greed, hatred and delusion are eradicated, will we eventually stop doing unskillful things.

223
00:21:08,863 --> 00:21:20,424
Many times we're going to give in to desire, to aversion, to harmfulness, and if we can't forgive ourselves, we're simply going to go on accumulating self-hate with its crushing effects on our hearts.

224
00:21:21,636 --> 00:21:26,545
We must know how to take refuge in the Dharma, the Truth, and especially the Lord of Karma.

225
00:21:27,066 --> 00:21:29,329
And we must learn how to take refuge in ourselves.

226
00:21:29,951 --> 00:21:31,794
We must learn how to forgive ourselves.

227
00:21:32,715 --> 00:21:40,188
We must realize there are going to be countless times we're going to give in, but our deepest resolution is never to give up.

228
00:21:41,049 --> 00:21:44,154
Battles will be lost, but the war must be won.

229
00:21:45,297 --> 00:21:47,019
This must be our life strategy.

230
00:21:47,692 --> 00:22:06,498
One very important tactic within this strategy is the routing of guilt, of shame, of dread, of worry, of restlessness, by the means of accepting responsibility, making amends, self-forgiving, and resolving to guard against occurrence, and so maintain a general balance and tranquility of mind.

231
00:22:08,580 --> 00:22:13,386
There is one other problem we need to deal with, that was hinted at in the first talk on guilt.

232
00:22:14,568 --> 00:22:16,872
What happens when we do something unwholesome?

233
00:22:17,392 --> 00:22:18,933
but don't know it to be unwholesome.

234
00:22:20,016 --> 00:22:22,759
Take, for instance, daydream and indulgent fantasy.

235
00:22:23,641 --> 00:22:30,049
We once thought them to be all right, but now, through the meditational experience, we've come to see them as quite corruptive.

236
00:22:31,151 --> 00:22:35,958
Eventually, we will come to suffer, for these fantasies lead to insatiability.

237
00:22:37,019 --> 00:22:46,992
Fantasies grow and grow until they've developed our desires to a point where they cannot be satisfied, such as dreaming about what we would do if we had a million pounds,

238
00:22:48,053 --> 00:22:51,596
That causes us to be dissatisfied and brings suffering.

239
00:22:51,615 --> 00:22:53,678
So here again we are back to the law of karma.

240
00:22:54,338 --> 00:22:56,840
When we do something harmful, harmfulness will arise.

241
00:22:58,162 --> 00:23:00,845
This suffering makes us reconsider what we are doing.

242
00:23:01,884 --> 00:23:08,832
More often than not we stop, though sometimes we need to suffer a little more until the suffering becomes greater than the pleasure.

243
00:23:10,272 --> 00:23:18,059
Not until there have been endless mornings of hangovers, sometimes not until the liver tweaks, does the dedicated drinker think of stopping,

244
00:23:18,884 --> 00:23:23,429
but this is how wisdom dawns on us and the balance of tranquility of mind is regained.

245
00:23:24,851 --> 00:23:38,605
Lily might not have thought she was doing anything particularly wrong, but when Mum came down on her like a ton of bricks, her ideas about what she could do with things that belong to her and things that belong to the family and others were sharpened.

246
00:23:39,046 --> 00:23:40,468
This was Lily's growth in wisdom.

247
00:23:42,028 --> 00:23:46,173
It also shows us how the Lord of Karma is always working for our benefit.

248
00:23:46,693 --> 00:23:48,777
This is the essential hope in the Dhamma.

249
00:23:49,597 --> 00:23:57,088
Everything in the universe, in one way or another, is conspiring to lead us to the end of suffering and the perfect peace of Nibbana.

250
00:23:59,673 --> 00:24:00,273
A final word.

251
00:24:01,435 --> 00:24:03,939
It's no good worrying about actions.

252
00:24:04,721 --> 00:24:05,561
What is done is done.

253
00:24:06,303 --> 00:24:09,928
All we can do is deal with the ongoing effects till they pass away.

254
00:24:10,528 --> 00:24:12,010
We need to cultivate patience.

255
00:24:13,413 --> 00:24:15,215
The Buddha gave us a wonderful image

256
00:24:15,836 --> 00:24:24,711
What would you think of a man shot by an arrow, who, when his friends came to help, would not allow them to pull it out until he had found out who shot it, who made it, and so on?

257
00:24:25,733 --> 00:24:26,875
He'd be dead before he knew.

258
00:24:26,915 --> 00:24:29,220
The arrow is the problem.

259
00:24:29,661 --> 00:24:30,521
Deal with the arrow.

260
00:24:31,042 --> 00:24:32,025
This is our freedom.

261
00:24:32,786 --> 00:24:34,588
We can deal with the present problems.

262
00:24:36,432 --> 00:24:39,718
Let's finish on a high note, the Buddha again in the Dhammapada.

263
00:24:40,761 --> 00:24:52,432
Rare in the world is the kind of person who, out of a sense of shame, refrains from wrongdoing and keeps himself awake, like a good horse that gives no cause to be whipped.

264
00:24:54,055 --> 00:25:00,361
Like a good horse stirred at the touch of a whip, be diligent, be alarmed at the endless rounds of rebirth.

265
00:25:01,020 --> 00:25:06,886
By faith, skilful conduct, effort, concentration and right understanding,

266
00:25:07,288 --> 00:25:14,583
Endowed in this way with wisdom, good practice and mindfulness, leave this immeasurable suffering behind.

267
00:25:18,651 --> 00:25:21,497
I hope you found this talk interesting and helpful.

268
00:25:22,459 --> 00:25:24,201
May all of you be happy and peaceful.

269
00:25:24,863 --> 00:25:27,828
May all of you attain the nirvanic peace within.

